Do not generate `Excel` file until you really have to. In case, you want to generate data without any specific formatting, charts, macros, etc. just generate `CSV` file with pure data. To read `JSON` and generate `CSV` you can use [Jackson][1] library which supports these two data formats. Just assume your `JSON` looks like below:

    {
      &quot;rows&quot;: [
        {
          &quot;id&quot;: 1,
          &quot;name&quot;: &quot;Vika&quot;,
          &quot;age&quot;: 27
        },
        {
          &quot;id&quot;: 2,
          &quot;name&quot;: &quot;Mike&quot;,
          &quot;age&quot;: 28
        }
      ]
    }

You, need to create `POJO` model which fits to that structure, deserialise `JSON` to objects and serialise objects to `CSV` format. Example solution, could look like below:

    import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonPropertyOrder;
    import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
    import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.SequenceWriter;
    import com.fasterxml.jackson.dataformat.csv.CsvMapper;
    import com.fasterxml.jackson.dataformat.csv.CsvSchema;
    
    import java.io.File;
    import java.util.List;
    
    public class JsonApp {
    
    	public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    		File jsonFile = new File(&quot;./resource/test.json&quot;).getAbsoluteFile();
    
    		ObjectMapper jsonMapper = new ObjectMapper();
    		Response response = jsonMapper.readValue(jsonFile, Response.class);
    
    		CsvMapper csvMapper = new CsvMapper();
    		CsvSchema schema = csvMapper.schemaFor(Item.class).withHeader();
    		SequenceWriter sequenceWriter = csvMapper.writer(schema).writeValues(System.out);
    		sequenceWriter.writeAll(response.getRows());
    	}
    }
    
    class Response {
    	private List&lt;Item&gt; rows;
    
    	// getters, setters
    }
    
    @JsonPropertyOrder({&quot;id&quot;, &quot;name&quot;, &quot;age&quot;})
    class Item {
    
    	private int id;
    	private String name;
    	private int age;
    
    	// getters, setters
    }


Above code prints:

    id,name,age
    1,Vika,27
    2,Mike,28

See also:

 - [jackson-dataformats-text][2]
 - [Intro to the Jackson ObjectMapper][3]


  [1]: https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-core
  [2]: https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-dataformats-text/tree/master/csv
  [3]: https://www.baeldung.com/jackson-object-mapper-tutorial

